eeking treatment for primary mood or anxiety concerns -- tSection VI: Veterans' issues -- t15. Military sexual trauma as a determinant in the development of mental and physical illness in male and female veterans -- t16. Educating medical professionals about suicide prevention among military veterans -- tSection VII: Public health, cultural, and legal issues -- t17. Does the physician density affect suicide rates among adolescents and young adults? -- t18. Suicidal behavior in Indian adolescents -- t19. American juvenile justice system: history in the making -- tSection VIII: Acknowlegements -- t20. About the editors -- t21. About Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai and the James J. Peters Veterans ' Administration Medical Center, New York City, United States -- t22. About the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development in Israel -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPsychiatric disorders in adolescents are an important social problem which is relevant to almost all healthcare professionals. According to the results of The National Comorbidity Survey-Adolescent Supplement (NCS-A), the lifetime prevalence of anxiety, behavior, mood, and substance use disorders among adolescents was 31.9%, 19.1%, 14.3%, and 11.4%, respectively. Approximately 40% of participants in this survey with one class of disorder also met criteria for another class of lifetime disorder. Comorbidity is increasingly recognized as a key feature of mental disorders among adolescents. Female adolescents are more likely than males to have mood and anxiety disorders, but less likely to have behavioral and substance use disorders. Regretfully, medical professionals are not sufficiently trained about adolescent psychiatric disorders. For example, primary care providers correctly identify less than a fourth of youth with a depressive or anxiety disorder. Also, many clinicians underestimate the importance of the problem of adolescent psychiatric illnesses and suicidal behavior. Lack of skilled medical providers impedes the delivery of needed services to adolescents with mental health issues. This coupled with a lag in the ability of primary health care services to incorporate psychiatric interventions, and a failure of public health initiatives to pay attention to adolescent mental health problems has led to continuing gaps in care over decades despite the public pronouncements of needs. In this book you will find relevant information for health professionals, since we believe that the mental health of adolescents is essential for sustaining healthy and productive societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aPsychiatry. 4aNational Comorbidity Survey-Adolescent Supplement. 4aPosttraumatic stress disorder. 4aPsychiatric disorders. 4aantidepressants. 4asuicide prevention. 7aMEDICAL / Psychiatry / General.2bisacsh1 aMeng, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Brien, Betsy S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackwood, Tracey A.1 aBoden, Eric.1 aBraquehais, María Dolores.1 aDe Álvaro, Raquel.1 aGanz, Debora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSamuel, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobry, Yuriy.1 aBoden, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuby, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForster, Christeen.1 aGanz, Debora.1 aPelletier, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/